[5] Cholera - Viet Nam
Date: Tue 29 Jul 2008
Source: VietNamNet Bridge [edited]
<http://english.vietnamnet.vn/social/2008/07/796115/>


The Health Ministry on 28 Jul 2008 reported to the government that
there were 441 acute diarrhea patients in 18 provinces and cities in
July, including 67 [documented] cholera patients, but no deaths.

On the same day, Nguyen Thanh Cong, Director of the Health Department
of the northern province of Hai Duong, announced that an acute
diarrhea epidemic had broken out in Tan Viet commune, Thanh Ha
district, Hai Duong, with 3 people positive for _Vibrio cholerae_.

These people ate food that contained the bacterium at a funeral in
Tan Viet commune. Well water taken from the home of 1 patient is also
positive for _Vibrio cholerae_.

[Byline: L Ha]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The following is from the commentary on a report on cholera from
ProMED-mail Mekong Basin Disease Surveillance (ProMED-MBDS) [Cholera
- Viet Nam (21) 20080729.2312]:

"To date [29 Jul 2008], the total number of cases reported in Viet
Nam since the beginning of this year (2008) has been 4143 acute
diarrhea cases and 649 cholera cases. However, no fatalities
associated with these outbreaks have been detected. The most recent
outbreak of acute diarrhea was reported from Tan Viet commune, Thanh
Ha district of Hai Duong province, where 3 cases of cholera were
detected (see prior PRO/MBDS posting Cholera - Viet Nam (20): Hai
Duong 20080728.2302).

It's also important to mention the recent identification of _Vibrio
cholera_ contamination of frozen fish filets imported to Norway from
Viet Nam (see PRO/MBDS Food poisoning, fish filets - Norway ex Viet
Nam: RFI 20080727.2295). Fortunately there have been no reported
cases of cholera associated with these contaminated fish filets as
yet (there was also contamination with staphylococcal toxin, which
did result in a single reported case of food poisoning in Norway
which led to the testing of the fish filets). - Mods.YMA/MPP"

A map of the country can be found at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/vietnam_admin01.jpg>.
- Mod.LL]

