[7] Cholera - India (Haryana)
Date: Fri 25 Jul 2008
Source: Express India [edited]
<http://www.expressindia.com/latest-news/Cholera-epidemic-remains-unchecked-13-more-cases-suspected/340265/>


As many as 13 more cases of suspected cholera were reported from the
Government Hospital, in Panchkula, on Thursday [24 Jul 2008]. The
health officials said that out of all the 13, the condition of 5
patients was serious as they were suffering from acute diarrhea. The
stool samples of the patients have been sent to the Post Graduate
Institute (PGI) of Medical Research in Chandigarh for confirmation of
the tests.

"All these cases have symptoms of cholera but we can confirm them
only when the PGI reports come after 2-3 days," said a local health
official.

The official count of cholera cases has now at 27 in the Panchkula
district. In the Government Hospital alone, 8 patients have succumbed
to the disease.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

Panchkula is in Haryana, a state in North India. It was carved out of
the state of Punjab in 1966. Haryana surrounds Delhi on 3 sides,
forming the northern, western, and southern borders of Delhi.
Consequently, a large area of Haryana is included in the National
Capital Region. The capital of Haryana is Chandigarh, which is
administered as a union territory and is also the capital of Punjab.
The previous discussion and a map of the state can be found at
<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haryana>. - Mod.LL]

******
[8] Cholera, diarrhea - India (Delhi)
Date: Fri 18 Jul 2008
Source: Daily Pioneer [edited]
<http://www.dailypioneer.com>[direct link to news story no longer
available. - Mod.LM]


Cholera has claimed 3 lives at Sector 7 JJ Colony in Dwarka of west
Delhi. About 70 more people have been detected having this disease.
According to residents of the colony, there is hardly any family in
the area that is not affected by the disease. According to residents,
a few victims have been admitted to the Deen Dayal Upadhaya Hospital.
Others have been admitted in nursing homes located in the nearby
areas.

Executive engineer Virender Kumar said, "After receiving complaints
of infected water, the DJB [Delhi Jal Board] has started supplying
water through DJB tankers." The number of water tankers has also been
increased. Samples of water are also being checked, said Kumar.
Meanwhile, municipal health officer NK Yadav said, "The deaths were
due to gastroenteritis and not cholera. We have been distributing
chlorine tablets and Delhi Jal Board has been informed in this
regard."

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

******
[9] Cholera - Indonesia (West Papua)
Date: Tue 29 Jul 2008
Source: Canada.com, Agence France-Presse (AFP) report [edited]
<http://www.canada.com/topics/news/world/story.html?id=601dd1df-d54b-4711-b851-f4c4ef988314>


At least 172 villagers have died in a cholera outbreak that has
triggered unrest in Indonesia's remote eastern Papua province, church
authorities said Tuesday [29 Jul 2008]. Church aid workers in the
Kamuu valley [West Papua] confirmed the victims had died from severe
diarrhea and vomiting caused by cholera, said Catholic brother Budi
Hermawan from the Jayapura archdiocese.

The source of the outbreak, which began in April 2008, was still
unknown, but the disease appeared to be spreading via drinking water
from a river and products in markets in the highland region, Hermawan
told AFP by phone from Jayapura.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[West Papua is the least populous province of Indonesia on the
western end of the island of New Guinea. It covers the Bird's Head
(or Doberai) Peninsula and surrounding islands. It can be found on a
map at
<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/West_Papua_(province)>. - Mod.LL]

[The outbreaks discussed in this update can also be found on the
HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at
<http://www.healthmap.org/promed>. - Mod.LL]
